 8. Real World Example
Login Form
import { useState } from "react";

function Login() {
  const [email, setEmail] = useState("");
  const [password, setPassword] = useState("");

  return (
    <>
      <input
        type="email"
        placeholder="Email"
        value={email}
        onChange={(e) => setEmail(e.target.value)}
      />

      <input
        type="password"
        placeholder="Password"
        value={password}
        onChange={(e) => setPassword(e.target.value)}
      />

      <button>Login</button>
    </>
  );
}

Industry applications work similarly.

Handling Form Submission
Syntax
<form onSubmit={handleSubmit}>

function App() {
  const [name, setName] = useState("");

  const handleSubmit = (e) => {
    e.preventDefault();

    alert(name);
  };

  return (
    <form onSubmit={handleSubmit}>
      <input
        value={name}
        onChange={(e) => setName(e.target.value)}
      />

      <button type="submit">
        Submit
      </button>
    </form>
  );
}


Why e.preventDefault()?

Normally form submission causes:

Page Reload

React apps don't want this.

So:

e.preventDefault();

stops reload.


in other after submitting the form it automatically reload  but in react that doesn't required 


multiple input using the one state input object 


We can use:

const [formData, setFormData] = useState({
  name: "",
  email: "",
  phone: ""
});
Update Input
const handleChange = (e) => {
  setFormData({
    ...formData,
    [e.target.name]: e.target.value
  });
};


spread data  copies the existing value 


Understanding Spread Operator
...formData

Copies existing values.

Example:

Before:

{
  name:"Ithesh",
  email:"abc@gmail.com"
}

Update name:

{
  ...formData,
  name:"John"
}

Result:

{
  name:"John",
  email:"abc@gmail.com"
}

9. Common Mistakes
Mistake 1

Missing value

<input onChange={handleChange} />

Not fully controlled.

Correct:

<input
  value={name}
  onChange={handleChange}
/>

Mistake 2

Forgetting preventDefault

const handleSubmit = () => {
}

Page reloads.

Correct:

e.preventDefault();

Mistake 3

Direct State Mutation

Wrong:

formData.name = "John";

Correct:

setFormData(...)


